# 🔐 Production RBAC Migration Plan
## localStorage → Database | Zero-Downtime, Zero Data Loss

> [!CAUTION]
> **LIVE PRODUCTION MIGRATION — NO BACKUP EXISTS**
> Every step must be reversible. Every query must be idempotent.
> This document is the single source of truth for the migration.

---

## Architecture Overview

### Current State (BROKEN)
```
┌─────────────┐                  ┌──────────────────┐
│   Browser    │                  │    Supabase DB    │
│             │                  │                  │
│ localStorage ├──── READS ──────▶│  (NEVER USED)    │
│ wms_user_    │                  │  permissions tbl │
│ permissions  │                  │  (role defaults) │
│             │                  │                  │
│ per-user     │                  │  profiles.role   │
│ { key: bool }│                  │  (L1/L2/L3)      │
└─────────────┘                  └──────────────────┘
   ⚠️ SOURCE OF TRUTH              ❌ IGNORED
```

### Target State (SECURE)
```
┌─────────────┐                  ┌──────────────────────────┐
│   Browser    │                  │       Supabase DB        │
│             │     API CALL     │                          │
│  App.tsx     ├────────────────▶│  user_permissions tbl    │
│  reads perms │                  │  (per-user overrides)    │
│  from DB     │                  │         ↓ merges with    │
│             │                  │  permissions tbl         │
│ localStorage │                  │  (role defaults)         │
│  REMOVED     │                  │         ↓                │
└─────────────┘                  │  get_effective_perms()   │
                                 │  (single function call)  │
                                 └──────────────────────────┘
                                    ✅ SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH
```

### Permission Resolution Priority
```
1. user_permissions   (per-user override — highest priority)
       ↓
2. permissions        (role default — L1/L2/L3 baseline)
       ↓
3. DENY BY DEFAULT    (no row = no access)
```

---

## Risk Analysis (PHASE 0)

### Identified Risks

| # | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|------|:----------:|:------:|------------|
| R1 | New table creation fails mid-transaction | Low | Low | Wrapped in `BEGIN/COMMIT`, idempotent `IF NOT EXISTS` |
| R2 | RLS policies lock out L3 users | Medium | **Critical** | Policies tested before enabling; `SECURITY DEFINER` helpers |
| R3 | Module name mismatch causes silent permission denial | High | High | Normalization mapping + validation queries |
| R4 | localStorage data lost before DB ingestion | Medium | Medium | Frontend exports data before deleting; staging table holds copy |
| R5 | Partial migration leaves split-brain state | Medium | **Critical** | Feature flag controls read source; rollback restores localStorage |
| R6 | `get_effective_permissions()` is slow | Low | Medium | Indexed columns; function result cached per-session |
| R7 | Concurrent L3 edits during migration | Low | Low | Single `ON CONFLICT` upsert prevents duplicates |

### Rollback Checkpoints

| Checkpoint | Trigger Condition | Action |
|------------|-------------------|--------|
| CP-0 | Before any DDL | Snapshot `permissions` count |
| CP-1 | After table creation | Verify table exists, zero rows |
| CP-2 | After data ingestion | Row count matches expected |
| CP-3 | After feature flag flip | Sanity check: L3 admin can still operate |
| CP-4 | After localStorage removal | Final parity check |

---

## PHASE 1 — Schema Design

### Entity Relationship

```mermaid
erDiagram
    profiles ||--o{ user_permissions : "has overrides"
    profiles ||--|| roles : "has role"
    roles ||--o{ permissions : "has defaults"
    profiles ||--o{ perm_migration_staging : "staging data"

    profiles {
        uuid id PK
        varchar role FK
        boolean is_active
    }

    roles {
        varchar id PK
        varchar name
        int level
    }

    permissions {
        uuid id PK
        varchar role_id FK
        varchar module
        varchar action
        boolean is_allowed
    }

    user_permissions {
        uuid id PK
        uuid user_id FK
        varchar module_name
        boolean can_view
        boolean can_create
        boolean can_edit
        boolean can_delete
        varchar source_role
        uuid overridden_by
        timestamptz overridden_at
        timestamptz created_at
        timestamptz updated_at
    }

    perm_migration_staging {
        uuid id PK
        uuid user_id FK
        jsonb raw_permissions
        varchar migration_status
        timestamptz ingested_at
    }
```

---

## PHASE 2 — Forward Migration SQL

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Run this in the **Supabase SQL Editor** as a single transaction.
> It is fully idempotent — safe to re-run if it fails partway.

### Script 1: `001_create_user_permissions.sql`

```sql
-- ============================================================================
-- MIGRATION 001: CREATE user_permissions TABLE
-- Purpose: Per-user granular permission overrides
-- Safety: Idempotent, backward compatible, does NOT modify existing tables
-- Rollback: Script 001_rollback.sql
-- ============================================================================

BEGIN;

-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- CHECKPOINT CP-0: Snapshot existing state
-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DO $$
DECLARE
  _profiles_count int;
  _perms_count int;
BEGIN
  SELECT count(*) INTO _profiles_count FROM public.profiles WHERE deleted_at IS NULL;
  SELECT count(*) INTO _perms_count FROM public.permissions;
  RAISE NOTICE '╔══════════════════════════════════════════════╗';
  RAISE NOTICE '║  PRE-MIGRATION SNAPSHOT                      ║';
  RAISE NOTICE '║  Active profiles: %                          ', _profiles_count;
  RAISE NOTICE '║  Permission rows: %                          ', _perms_count;
  RAISE NOTICE '╚══════════════════════════════════════════════╝';
END $$;

-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 1. CREATE MODULE NAME NORMALIZATION MAP
-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- This mapping table bridges frontend ↔ DB naming differences.
-- It is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for module identifiers going forward.

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS public.module_registry (
  module_key    varchar NOT NULL,               -- canonical key (e.g. 'stock-movements')
  display_name  varchar NOT NULL,               -- human label
  parent_module varchar,                        -- null for top-level, parent key for subs
  sort_order    int DEFAULT 0,
  is_active     boolean DEFAULT true,
  created_at    timestamptz DEFAULT now(),
  CONSTRAINT module_registry_pkey PRIMARY KEY (module_key)
);

-- Seed canonical module list (idempotent via ON CONFLICT)
INSERT INTO public.module_registry (module_key, display_name, parent_module, sort_order) VALUES
  ('dashboard',                   'Dashboard',                      NULL, 10),
  ('items',                       'Item Master',                    NULL, 20),
  ('inventory',                   'Inventory',                      NULL, 30),
  ('stock-movements',             'Stock Movements',                NULL, 40),
  ('packing.sticker-generation',  'Sticker Generation',            'packing', 50),
  ('packing.packing-details',     'Packing Details',               'packing', 51),
  ('packing.packing-list-invoice','Packing List — Invoice',        'packing', 52),
  ('packing.packing-list-sub-invoice','Packing List — Sub Invoice','packing', 53),
  ('orders',                      'Blanket Orders',                 NULL, 60),
  ('releases',                    'Blanket Releases',               NULL, 70),
  ('forecast',                    'Forecasting',                    NULL, 80),
  ('planning',                    'MRP Planning',                   NULL, 90),
  ('users',                       'User Management',                NULL, 100),
  ('notifications',               'Notifications',                  NULL, 110)
ON CONFLICT (module_key) DO NOTHING;

-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 2. CREATE user_permissions TABLE
-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS public.user_permissions (
  id              uuid NOT NULL DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4(),
  user_id         uuid NOT NULL,
  module_name     varchar NOT NULL,           -- references module_registry.module_key
  can_view        boolean NOT NULL DEFAULT false,
  can_create      boolean NOT NULL DEFAULT false,
  can_edit        boolean NOT NULL DEFAULT false,
  can_delete      boolean NOT NULL DEFAULT false,
  source_role     varchar,                    -- role at time of override (audit trail)
  overridden_by   uuid,                       -- L3 user who set this override
  overridden_at   timestamptz,                -- when the override was set
  created_at      timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
  updated_at      timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),

  CONSTRAINT user_permissions_pkey PRIMARY KEY (id),
  CONSTRAINT user_permissions_user_fkey FOREIGN KEY (user_id)
    REFERENCES public.profiles(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,
  CONSTRAINT user_permissions_module_fkey FOREIGN KEY (module_name)
    REFERENCES public.module_registry(module_key),
  CONSTRAINT user_permissions_overrider_fkey FOREIGN KEY (overridden_by)
    REFERENCES public.profiles(id),
  CONSTRAINT user_permissions_unique UNIQUE (user_id, module_name)
);

-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 3. INDEXES
-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_user_perms_user_id
  ON public.user_permissions(user_id);

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_user_perms_module
  ON public.user_permissions(module_name);

CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_user_perms_user_module
  ON public.user_permissions(user_id, module_name);

-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 4. AUTO-UPDATE updated_at TRIGGER
-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

-- Reuse existing trigger function if available, else create
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION public.set_updated_at()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  NEW.updated_at = now();
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SET search_path = public;

DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS trigger_user_permissions_updated_at ON public.user_permissions;
CREATE TRIGGER trigger_user_permissions_updated_at
  BEFORE UPDATE ON public.user_permissions
  FOR EACH ROW
  EXECUTE FUNCTION public.set_updated_at();

-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- 5. PERMISSION CHANGE AUDIT TRIGGER
-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION public.audit_permission_change()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  INSERT INTO public.audit_log (
    user_id,
    action,
    target_type,
    target_id,
    old_value,
    new_value
  ) VALUES (
    COALESCE(NEW.overridden_by, auth.uid()),
    CASE TG_OP
      WHEN 'INSERT' THEN 'GRANT_PERMISSION'
      WHEN 'UPDATE' THEN 'UPDATE_PERMISSION'
      WHEN 'DELETE' THEN 'REVOKE_PERMISSION'
    END,
    'user_permission',
    COALESCE(NEW.user_id, OLD.user_id)::text,
    CASE WHEN TG_OP = 'INSERT' THEN NULL ELSE jsonb_build_object(
      'module', OLD.module_name,
      'can_view', OLD.can_view,
      'can_create', OLD.can_create,
      'can_edit', OLD.can_edit,
      'can_delete', OLD.can_delete
    ) END,
    CASE WHEN TG_OP = 'DELETE' THEN NULL ELSE jsonb_build_object(
      'module', NEW.module_name,
      'can_view', NEW.can_view,
      'can_create', NEW.can_create,
      'can_edit', NEW.can_edit,
      'can_delete', NEW.can_delete
    ) END
  );
  RETURN COALESCE(NEW, OLD);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER SET search_path = public;

DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS trigger_audit_perm_change ON public.user_permissions;
CREATE TRIGGER trigger_audit_perm_change
  AFTER INSERT OR UPDATE OR DELETE ON public.user_permissions
  FOR EACH ROW
  EXECUTE FUNCTION public.audit_permission_change();

-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- CHECKPOINT CP-1: Verify table created
-- ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DO $$
BEGIN
  IF EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM information_schema.tables
             WHERE table_schema = 'public' AND table_name = 'user_permissions') THEN
    RAISE NOTICE '✅ CP-1: user_permissions table created successfully';
  ELSE
    RAISE EXCEPTION '❌ CP-1 FAILED: user_permissions table was NOT created';
  END IF;

  IF EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM information_schema.tables
             WHERE table_schema = 'public' AND table_name = 'module_registry') THEN
    RAISE NOTICE '✅ CP-1: module_registry table created successfully';
  ELSE
    RAISE EXCEPTION '❌ CP-1 FAILED: module_registry table was NOT created';
  END IF;
END $$;

COMMIT;
```

